The Plan 9 linker learns named externs, GC, and loses a family of
undefined-memory bugs.

Named externs (compiler-rt libcalls): phantom atoms with GOT slots,
resolved at flush against the same-named zcu export (fail-by-name if
missing, validated against recycled Export.Index slots). CodeGen's
genExternSymbolRef and the Select .symbol operand emit ds-relative GOT
loads/calls; Lower promotes call/jmp memory operands to 64-bit (call m32
has no encoding).

GC (gated on gc_sections, i.e. release modes): reference edges recorded at
the four linker entry points every code-side reference flows through
(seeNav / lazy symbols / named globals / lowerUav) plus relocs for
data-side pointers; flushModule marks from the _start export and skips
unmarked atoms (no code, no syms, GOT slot zeroed — the table is now
@memset). This is what keeps in-zcu compiler-rt from bloating binaries
toward the 2MB text boundary, which is now also a hard link error
(the kernel maps data at roundup(text_end, 2MB); a fixed 0x400000 data
base past that boundary would corrupt every GOT reference silently).

Robustness, each a real bug found landing zig build natively:
- bases initialized in createEmpty (only open() set them; the in-process
  cmdBuild flow goes createEmpty+makeWritable and produced offset-0 atoms
  and entry=0 binaries: "exec header invalid")
- entry derived from the _start export's atom offset after layout
  (writeSyms's name scan read an undefined sym value on this path)
- createAtom no longer leaves .code undefined: deinit frees
  code.getOwnedCode() for every atom, and phantom atoms never assign it —
  under the C backend undefined is a deterministic 0xAA fill, so deinit
  freed wild pointers (the years-latent "heap corruption" that forced a
  retain-forever allocator; found by fingerprinting 0xAA frees + an rbp
  backtrace on cirno). Same for pre-flush lazy-sym names (zero-len static
  name until updateLazySymbolAtom assigns the real one).
- emit-fd validated/reopened at flush; kernel errstr in write diagnostics;
  seeNav allocates got_index on the found-existing path; getOffset handles
  .memory/.indirect operands.

